Boil a full #kettle{}. Remove the @lamb steaks{2} from your fridge to allow them to
come up to room temperature.

Meanwhile, chop the @baking potato{1}(peeled into 2cm chunks) and
@sweet potato{1}(peeled into 2cm chunks).

Pour the boiled water into a large #saucepan{} on high heat with
@salt{1/2%tsp}.

Add the potatoes to the water and cook until you can easily slip a knife
through, ~{15-18%minutes}.

== Marinade ==

Add the lamb steaks to a medium #bowl{} with the @peri peri seasoning{1%sachet},
@olive oil{1%tbsp} for the marinade and a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Rub to coat all over.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat.

== Cooking the Lamb ==

Return the (now empty) #frying pan{} to high heat.

Once hot, lay the steaks into the pan and fry until browned and medium-rare,
~{8-10%minutes} total. Turn every ~{2%minutes}.

> TIP: Cook each side for 1-2 min more if you like it more well done.

Once cooked, transfer to a #board{}, cover with #foil{} and allow to rest for
a couple of minutes.

> IMPORTANT: The lamb is safe to eat when browned on the outside.

== Peas ==

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @olive oil{} in a #small saucepan{} on
medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @peas{120%g} and stir-fry for ~{2-3%minutes}. Season with
@salt{} and @pepper{}.

== Hot Honey Sauce and Mash ==

Wipe out the (now empty) frying pan and return to low heat.

Melt the @butter{20%g}, then stir in the @hot sauce{50%g} and @honey{15%g}.
Bring to the boil, then remove from the heat.

> TIP: If your honey has hardened, pop it in a bowl of hot water for 1min.

Once the potatoes are cooked, drain in a #colander{} and return to the pan,
off the heat. Add a knob of butter and a splash of @?milk{} and mash until
smooth using a #potato masher{}. Season with salt and pepper.

== To Serve ==

Slice the peri peri lamb widthways into 1cm thick slices and share between your
plates.

Serve the mash and peas alongside.

Drizzle the hot honey sauce over the steaks.

Enjoy!